{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a23ad5ac-fa54-4258-abb7-718cb1b4d25b","content":"Here's the evaluation performance analysis for `EvalHeavy.csproj`:\n\n## Issues Found\n\n### 1. File I/O During Evaluation (High Impact)\n**Line 13:** `$([System.IO.File]::ReadAllText('build-notes.txt'))`\n\nProperty functions that perform disk I/O execute during evaluation—every build, every IDE reload. This blocks the evaluation phase with synchronous file reads.\n\n**Fix:** Move file reading to a target that runs at build time, or use a build task instead.\n\n### 2. Broad Recursive Glob (Medium Impact)\n**Line 9:** `<AdditionalFiles Include=\"**\\*.*\" ...>`\n\nThis walks the entire directory tree during evaluation. Only `bin`/`obj` are excluded—any large subdirectory (packages, `.git`, test artifacts) will be scanned. Add exclusions via `DefaultItemExcludes` or narrow the glob pattern.\n\n### 3. Chained Import Depth (Low Impact)\nThe import chain is 3 levels deep: `.csproj → level1.props → level2.props → level3.props`. Currently shallow, but this pattern scales poorly. Each import requires file resolution and parsing. Consider flattening or consolidating if the chain grows.\n\n---\n\n**Priority:** Fix the `File::ReadAllText` call first—it's the most costly per-evaluation. Then tighten the glob.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"8c43a942-37b9-4195-8691-1922f1cfc582","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Now I have a complete picture of the project. Let me analyze the evaluation performance issues.\n\nIssues I can identify:\n\n1. **File I/O property function** (line 13 in .csproj): `$([System.IO.File]::ReadAllText('build-notes.txt'))` - This reads a file during evaluation, which is expensive because it involves disk I/O during what should be a fast in-memory phase.\n\n2. **Overly broad glob pattern** (line 9): `**\\*.*` - The `AdditionalFiles` item uses a recursive wildcard that walks the entire directory tree. If there are large directories (node_modules, .git, packages, etc.), this would be very slow. While `bin` and `obj` are excluded, other large directories are not.\n\n\n3. **Deep import chain** (3 levels deep): The project imports through multiple property files, and while this particular depth isn't problematic, it shows a pattern that becomes severely costly when chains exceed 20 levels, since each import requires file resolution and parsing overhead.","outputTokens":604,"requestId":"DBCC:12FCC3:AB0DB43:B9F7ABA:69FD39C9"},"id":"80b00558-ec11-4812-9072-84dbd3d14657","timestamp":"2026-05-08T01:18:17.061Z","parentId":"cc033c79-417c-4eff-9882-dbfb6c1a0f4e"}
